## Migrated Code for .NET 8

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    /// <summary>
    /// Executes work with a timeout using cooperative cancellation.
    /// The work delegate must check the CancellationToken to respond to cancellation.
    /// </summary>
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }

    /// <summary>
    /// Overload for async work.
    /// </summary>
    public async Task<T> ExecuteWithTimeoutAsync<T>(Func<CancellationToken, Task<T>> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            return await Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

## Usage (before → after)

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework):
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(() => ComputeExpensiveResult(), TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER (.NET 8) — work must cooperate with cancellation:
var executor = new TimedExecutor();
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(token =>
{
    foreach (var item in items)
    {
        token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
        Process(item);
    }
    return finalResult;
}, TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

## Critical Pitfalls

| Pitfall | Explanation |
|---------|-------------|
| **Cancellation isn't immediate** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation only works at checkpoints where `token.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` is called. Long-running code between checks won't stop. |
| **Not disposing `CancellationTokenSource`** | Leaks internal timers. Always wrap in `using`. |
| **Uncooperative code won't stop** | If `work` ignores the token (e.g., calls a blocking native API), the task continues running after timeout. For truly uncooperative code, move it to a child `Process` and call `Process.Kill`. |
| **Catching `OperationCanceledException` too broadly** | Use `when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)` to distinguish your timeout from upstream cancellation. |
| **Signature change is breaking** | `Func<T>` → `Func<CancellationToken, T>` requires updating all callers. |

## If Work Cannot Be Modified to Accept a Token

For legacy code that can't cooperate (e.g., third-party library calls), the task will keep running after timeout — you're just abandoning it:

```csharp
// Fire-and-forget fallback (work continues running in background!)
public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
{
    using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);
    var task = Task.Run(work);

    try
    {
        return task.WaitAsync(cts.Token).GetAwaiter().GetResult();
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        // ⚠️ task is still running — it's abandoned, not killed
        throw new TimeoutException($"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
    }
}
```

> ⚠️ This is **not equivalent** to the original — the thread keeps running. If you need true termination of uncooperative code, isolate it in a separate **process** and use `Process.Kill()`.
